## Problem

I need to create an HTML element, [just how the `video_player` does it](https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues/49634#issuecomment-580873923), and let JW Player control it.  
The JavaScript syntax JW Player expects is `jwplayer("<DIV ID>")`, where `DIV ID` is the `id` of a `<div>` element. Example [can be found here](https://developer.jwplayer.com/jwplayer/docs/jw8-javascript-api-reference#section-jwplayer-div-setup-options).  
I want to integrate the HTML div element **into Flutter** to achieve the same effect that `video_player` does.

### HTML equivalent

This is **everything** required to make the whole player work:

<details><summary>Click to expand</summary>

```js
// In head:
// <script src="https://cdn.jwplayer.com/libraries/cdD21GnT.js"></script>

// In body:
// <div id="jw-player-example"></div>

// In JS:
jwplayer("jw-player-example").setup({file: "https://content.jwplatform.com/manifests/VKDKBLZm.m3u8"})
```

</details>

I only want to do this and have the `div` in an `HTMLElementView`, but Flutter seems to be doing something that makes this not work.


## It does not work in Flutter

The concept seems straight forward, however, there is a big problem: JW Player does not seem t obe happy with how Flutter inserts DOM elements, i.e. Flutter inserts them into a ***shadow DOM***.  
The [`jwplayer` function](https://github.com/jwplayer/jwplayer/blob/ff08b4c3e0a24a5f27ebb1b2dfac46217d56da38/src/js/jwplayer.js#L22) actually does not only accept strings - it also [accepts DOM elements directly](https://github.com/jwplayer/jwplayer/blob/ff08b4c3e0a24a5f27ebb1b2dfac46217d56da38/src/js/jwplayer.js#L42). However, I have no idea how to pass the element I create to that function.  

Below I will showcase a few approaches that _did not work_:

<details><summary>Click to expand</summary>

```dart
const viewType = 'jw-player-view';

final div = DivElement()..id = viewType;

// ignore: UNDEFINED_PREFIXED_NAME
ui.platformViewRegistry.registerViewFactory(
  viewType,
  (int viewId) => div,
);

// jwplayer("jw-player-view")
(js.context['jwplayer'] as js.JsFunction).apply([viewType]);
// Does not work because the element is created in the shadow DOM.

// jwplayer(div)
(js.context['jwplayer'] as js.JsFunction).apply([div]);
// Seems to kind of work to some extent (no exception), but the player does not appear
// to really do anything to the actual DOM element because it probably is only an object
// that does not actually point to the dom. jwplayer().getContainer() will reveal a "jw-flag-play-rejected".

// jwplayer(document.getElementsByTagName('flt-platform-view')[0].shadowRoot.querySelector('#jw-player-view'))
// This seems the most promising, but I can only get it to work from the JS console and it
// has the problem of not displaying anything in any way again.
// I assume that the CSS that should apply does not reach the element because it is in the shadow DOM.


document.getElementsByTagName('flt-platform-view')[0].append(_div);
// Does not seem to add the element to the DOM and more importantly I will not be able to use it
// in a HTMLElementView.
```

</details>

### Putting the script into the shadow DOM

I saw that @hterkelsen proposed the following [in a similar seeming issue](https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues/40080#issuecomment-531040550):

> If you want to bundle JS with your platform view, you could register a `BodyElement` with a `ScriptElement`. Will this give you the functionality you need?

<details><summary>Click to see the problem with that</summary>

I had two problems with that: first of all, I did not get it to work with the `platformViewRegistry`:

```dart
final body = BodyElement()..id = 'BODYELEMENTID';

final script = ScriptElement()
  // Inserts cloud hosted JW Player into the shadow DOM.
  ..src = 'https://cdn.jwplayer.com/libraries/ID.js';

body.insertAdjacentElement('afterBegin', script);

// ignore: UNDEFINED_PREFIXED_NAME
ui.platformViewRegistry.registerViewFactory(
  'shadow-body',
  (int viewId) => body,
);
```

This does not do anything - so I do not really have an idea how to use it. It seems that I first need to return it
to an `HTMLElementView`, but that does also not really seem to help.

More importantly however, even when I inserted the element from the JS console, it as though the
`jwplayer` object was still part of the main document and **still not able to access the div element**.

</details>

## Questions

Is there any way I can make JW Player accept the HTML elements created in Flutter?  

1. Is there a way to achieve this currently?  
2. Is there maybe even a way to **not use** a shadow DOM if we want?

