From reading through StackOverflow, Flutter users make a common mistake: they write:

```dart
class MyStateful extends StatefulWidget {
  const MyStateful({Key key, this.props}): super(key: key);

  final int props;

  MyStatefulState createState() {
    return MyStatefulState(props);
  }
}

class MyStatefulState extends State<MyStateful> {
  MyStatefulState(this.props);

  int props;

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return Text('$props');
  }
}
```


when they should instead do:


```dart
class MyStateful extends StatefulWidget {
  const MyStateful({Key key, this.props}): super(key: key);

  final int props;

  MyStatefulState createState() => MyStatefulState();
}

class MyStatefulState extends State<MyStateful> {
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return Text('${widget.props}');
  }
}
```


This causes issues.

For example, this SO question is one of the most popular ones:
https://stackoverflow.com/questions/50818770/passing-data-to-a-stateful-widget/50818870#50818870

It is also regular for people to ask why `State` doesn't get updated in that situation, like https://stackoverflow.com/questions/59130099/how-does-the-stateful-vs-stateless-distinction-affect-when-widgets-will-be-rebu




A linter rule like `no_state_constructor` that warns if there's a custom constructor on `State` should help people solve this issue naturally.

