I think the definition, examples, or naming of the [ScrollDirection](https://api.flutter.dev/flutter/rendering/ScrollDirection-class.html) enum values are inconsistent with the behaviour, though I'm not sure what the original intent with the naming was.

*ScrollDirection.forward* says:

> Scrolling is happening in the positive scroll offset direction.
>
> For example, for the GrowthDirection.forward part of a vertical AxisDirection.down list, this means the content is moving up, exposing lower content. 

I'm finding that for both a RenderViewport with AxisDirection.down and a RenderSliverList in that RenderViewport with GrowthDirection.forward that when I scroll down (i.e. expose lower content), the scroll offsets for both increase from zero (`renderViewport.offset.pixels` and `renderSliverList.constraints.scrollOffset`), but the `userScrollDirection` (`renderViewport.offset.userScrollDirection` and `renderSliverList.constraints.userScrollDirection`) is  ScrollDirection.reverse.  See tests at bottom for a demonstration of the behaviours.

At the very least, it seems we need to swap the examples given in the documentation of ScrollDirection.forward and .reverse.  Though I'm wondering if the value returned for userScrollDirection should be switched so that when the user is scrolling down (revealing more data at the bottom) in a AxisDirection.down RenderViewport, and in a RenderSliver in that viewport with growthDirection of GrowthDirection.forward, the userScrollDirection should be forward.  However, at the same time, I wonder if switching that behaviour would cause problems for existing client code.

I'm happy to fix this issue and submit a PR, but I'm not sure what the preferred solution would be.

### Demonstration tests

These tests demo the issue.  I would expect all of them to pass if the documentation for ScrollDirection.forward was correct; however, the tests for ScrollDirection fail while the tests for offset pass (as noted by comments before the last line on each test):

```dart
